title: Ender 2 Heat Bed Cable Strain Relief

description.text:
Strain Relief for Heated Bed Cable on Ender 2

Here is a plate to be mounted with washers and nuts under your heated bed.
I highly recommend insulating your bed and using the appropriate file.
I also recommend using the 3 screw version to hold planarity

I have made 4 versions:

ender_retain_3_insul.stl I recommend this file
ender_retain_3_no insul.stl Use this if you don't insulate bed

ender_retain_2_insul.stl Use this if you must print a smaller version- but prone to skewing

ender_retain_2_no insul.stl Use this if you must print smaller version and no insulation

I recommend printing in PETG or PLA Plus or other higher temp plastics.

it is stronger if printed with the main body flat on bed and few supports.

It gets attached to the bed's 3 screws, lock down with washers and nuts.
and I have made it to fit over bed insulation.

Use a cable tie over the connector block on the heat bed - most important, add others to secure cable.

If you haven't already, you can insulate your heat bed and increase its performance with these easy steps:
1 buy
2 Foam insulation tape:
3 https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B0195UF3SO/ref=oh_aui_search_detailpage?ie=UTF8&psc=1
and

Foil Tape:
https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B000NG622Q/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o07_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1
1 Cut and stick the foam to the underside of your heat bed, leave it about 1/8" away from edges, cut holes for screws, do not cover soldered ends of heat bed connector.
2 cover entire bottom with metal foil to seal in heat. Let foil wrap around sides of heated and burnish down with your fingernail then trim.
do not cover or touch the soldered connector**

Next:
1 Now mount your cable protector cover over the 3 screws and add a nut to each screw and tighten in place
2 Now assemble cables and add zip ties in two places to secure cables, and mount to your machine!

Please note: I am constantly improving the files.
I am now printing each of these new improvements and until I have printed, tested and mounted each, I am going to leave the label work in progress.

I have tested the two versions with insulation. I cannot test others if anyone else wants to give feedback.

If you make one please photograph and post it to this page!!!

title: Ender Control Box with SD converter and light switch

description.text:
Finished and Working! This has been printed and tested and refined 10 times, is good to go!

This is a control box cover for Ender 2 which gets the display up at a comfortable angle and adds a mirco SD to Full sized SD reader and a light switch.

There are two versions:

End2Contr8.stl has 52mms clearance between X gantry and rear of raised control box.

End2Contr10.stl is a new version with 65+mms between X gantry and rear of raised control box for passage of larger blower fans and EZABL.

Added an optional face plate for version 10, incase you are printing with the LCD face down this can cover the different print finish from the bed, and also cover the screws, glue with temporary glue so you can remove if needed, I used spray mount, but can use glue stick or other.

Version 8 is very comfortable for the screen angle but you cannot mount fans or instruments which stick out much further than original print head assembly.

If you print the version 10 on the face of the display screen it practically needs no supports!

mounting steps

  1. mount display inside of the housing with its cable harness in place (important that you do this first)

  2. add light and on off switches

  3. add SD card reader

      1. glue SD card reader in place with a small bit of hot glue from inside (it fits very snuggly) and use a bit of hot glue to hold ribbon flat to top of housing and position correctly to enter into lower right micro SD slot.
  5. attach all connectors, longer ones first then the short ones, make sure your wires are all going out back between both raised brass stand offs, and screw cover in place.

good to go!

To buy:

switch:
https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B071DNCFW1/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o04_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

SD converter:
Amazon: http://a.co/4kNZiRn

I added a light switch which powers my LED bar https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2700450.

You attach the power for the LEDs to the Main PSU Red wire to V+ black wire to COM, split one of the wires and put the switch in the middle of it.

I added a red and black wire to the k-fan outlet once inside the unit so I can easily add a bed fan later.

see video of work in progress: https://youtu.be/WvB6cS54RYQ

If you make one please photograph and post it to this page!!!

description.text:
This is a Talkbox. Not necessarily for a guitar, but that's certainly where I've seen them most.

Most designs seem to feature a horn tweeter with a long piece of garden hose reaching fro the floor. I decided to make mine pocket sized, so it has a small speaker, and a short piece of hose.

Essentially, it's a means to attach a piece of pipe to a speaker. It's a box containing a 4W speaker, connected to a piece of garden hose.

The theory is that the sound travels up the pipe, into the player's mouth, where they can shape it, like Ritchie Sambora https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tXN22O_R9GQ.

The speaker I used was a Maplin part N25KJ 28x40mm oval speaker. The base could easily be remodelled for other sizes / shapes, though.

Use of this device will require an amplifier. I suggest you connect the device to the headphone output of a regular amp or maybe a pocket-sized practice amp. You may need a microphone and a second amp, then to amplify the sound, as it effectively comes out of your mouth.

description.text:
This is a battery modification for a Taranis Q X7S that replaces the Nimh 2000mah battery pack with 2: LG 3500mah LI-Ion batteries (note: LG has some of the only "real" >2000mah Li-Ion batteries). I used a charger board and a 5.5x2.1mm panel mount charger plug.
Update: the original STL back plate has been updated for a better fit.

Search string for charger board: Intelligent Balance Charging Protection Board 2S Packs 18650 lithium Satellite

Search string for panel mount: 5.5mm x 2.1mm DC Power Jack Socket Female Panel Mount Connector plug

I printed it in ABS with supports due to the really small tabs that catch and hold the plate. The panel mount plug was 10.9mm, but due to the threads I made the hole for it 11.2mm which is still a tight fit but can still be screwed into the hole.

A new STL file has been uploaded (*_v2.stl) that adds a 6.8mm hole for a short clear acrylic rod to be inserted in to act as a light pipe and show the state of the charger board LED's. You will want to order a 1/4" (around 6.67mm) acrylic rod, and cut a short length off (around 6mm in length). Polish the 2 cut ends with fine grit sandpaper and insert it into the hole.

Note: you will want to print this with high density infill to make sure the tabs have enough strength (I used 50% infill).

I visited a colleague at home recently and as I was going to be meeting his six year old son Pi, I created a small model for him and took it along as a gift. Although I modelled it from scratch to look like the name Pi when stood on its end, I took inspiration from madscifi's excellent Tiny Toy Dump Truck http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:9710 As it is apparently PI day tomorrow, I thought that others might like a copy. It prints in about an hour with no assembly required.
So far, I've printed it a Makerware "Low" which is 0.3mm, 2 shells, 10% infill, 90mm/s, NO SUPPORT, no raft.

This parametric Sphere Cutter script will allow you to easily create jewelry accessoriers. You can create rings and bracelets from a sphere basic shape.
Gem inserts are available. The idea of cutting spheres for rings is similar to "Ring a Thing" http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:13902

Open the script with OpenScad. Set your parameters and check the result. There are 3 different styles for cutting the side walls of the sphere.
You can cut sidewalls with another sphere (ctyps) or a flat plain (ctypf).
The cutting position is determined by two x-values, the upper (x1, fx1) and lower (x2,fx2) half of object's thickness.
The third method is the central cone (ctypu) which is defined by a distance from the center of the object (ux) and the half of cone's angle (ualpha). Examples:
sp2ri_01.stl = sphere ring with a gem insert (green gem)
sp2ri_02.stl = bracelet

This eliminates the need for the "Tilted Adapter for Noctua UPGRADE" and assumes you have a 40mm x 10mm fan for extruder cooling. The 40mm x 20mm fan will prevent the limit switch from triggering - DO NOT USE.

title: Sonoff Enclosure with Push Button and Strain Relief

description.text:
This is an enclosure for the Sonoff 10A Wifi controlled switch. This Sonoff module is very popular because of its attractive price. But it only allows to splice it into 2-wire cables that don't have ground.
If you want to control an outlet that does need a ground wire then that wire has to be outside of the Sonoff module which makes the entire solution less esthetical and most likely also unsafe.
This enclosure fits the Sonoff module together with all the wiring and adds additional cable strain reliefs for improved safety. The strain relief only needs a small zip tie, no screws required.
This enclosure also keeps the option of manual control by adding a simple push button. The button only has to be placed in the proper location in the case before closing the case and allows to operate the push button of the Sonoff module inside.
Furthermore, the Sonoff module features a green control LED to indicate its switch status. The enclosure has an area with a thin wall for this LED to shine through. If you should use some non-translucent filament then you can go into the scad file and uncomment the corresponding line to get an actual hole for the LED.

Notes:

This can be printed with either ABS or PLA. I used a 0.4mm nozzle with 0.3mm layer height and 25% infill. No support needed.

title: Bowden E3D V6 Mount For Geeetech Prusa i3 Pro B

description.text:
This design is to allow the fitment of an E3D v6 hot end to a Geetech Prusa i3 Pro B although it can probably be used with others if required. It's a remix of my earlier design that was aimed mainly at people using a direct mount extruder rather than Bowden. This design is much simplified over the original and it was simpler to remix it rather than add the options into the existing project.

It's designed to mount to the rework x carriage and, for Geetech users in particular, the Geetech customisation of the X Carriage contained in one of my other projects:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1585254

Using the Geetech cutout version of the X-Carriage together with this mount allows the reuse of the original X axis linear bearings. Even with the addition of the bed levelling sensor this mount, combined with the modified x carriage maximises the available x axis movement.

The OpenSCAD source file is customisable so you can produce your own variations fairly easily although I've included stl files of pretty much every variation anyway !

The position of the hot end nozzle on the mount is critical for the Geetech i3 to ensure you also get maximum Y axis travel. If the nozzle is too far out from the X axis then you lose travel at the 0 end and if it's too close you lose travel at the 200mm end. The mount is designed to be optimum for the Geetech Prusa i3 (Acrylic 8mm frame) but this distance is one of the many variables at the top of the OpenSCAD source file to allow this to be matched to your printer.

In addition to the print you will need...

2 x M3x15 bolts and nuts for the hot end clamp
2 x M3 x 30 bolts for the extruder mount
4 x M4 x 20 Bolts and nuts to fix the most to the x carriage.

I use a capacitance level sensor (6-36v 1-10mm) as it works well with the glass bed.

I've also added the .stl file for a cooling fan duct that bolts onto a bracket attached to the hot end clamp and takes the original Geetech 40mm fan from the extruder. It's not the most optimised design but seems to work fairly well. The OpenSCAD file is a bit of a mess at the moment and I'll post it when I get time to clean it up. I printed it as positioned in the .stl file without any supports. Ironically using a cooling fan will improve the print of the duct so the second prototype was a much better print than the second so you might end up having to print this twice, using the first print to cool the second.

description.text:
My five year old daughter asked me if she could print out a heart she drew one day. She happened to be very specific, so I asked her to design it with me. At that point I was in the middle of printing out parts for my students on my personal printer (school Makerbot was down) and was swamped with work, but what designer can say no to that.

We made this heart very simply with a mirrored half circle and an arc, then extruded and filleted it in AutoCAD. It was her first 3D CAD design and she did a great job. She has continued to ask to design with me and I hope she keeps the ideas coming. She simply adores these hearts and keeps them in her homemade treasure box so I hope you will adore them too!

title: Oculus Sensor Drop Ceiling Magnetic Mount

description.text:
I made a simple Oculus Rift sensor holder that is held to my drop ceiling rails by 12x6 magnets. I have two magnets in each slot for extra strength. Although I'm using them with my drop ceiling, you could attach them to any magnetic surface pretty easily. I got the magnets at Home Depot in their magnet section by fasteners. I used a standard 1/4-20 bolt that is 3/4" long.

If you do end up making these, I would greatly appreciate it if you let me know. I don't do too many designs but I'm always glad to hear when my design helps someone else out.

Thanks for looking!
